      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Dissent on a Park</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Andrew Alpern letter disputes June 29 Currents column, which described new Balsley Park at 57th Street and Ninth Avenue as 'urban renewal;' says 'urban arrogance' would be more apt description (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Currents column described the new Balsley Park at 57th Street and Ninth Avenue as ''urban renewal'' (''Plaza Into Park, With Coffee Kiosk and Greenmarket,'' June 29). A more apt description would be ''urban arrogance.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Currents column described the new Balsley Park at 57th Street and Ninth Avenue as ''urban renewal'' (''Plaza Into Park, With Coffee Kiosk and Greenmarket,'' June 29). A more apt description would be ''urban arrogance.''</p>
        <p>The design is inappropriate to the 19th-century buildings on the opposite three corners, and at odds with the vastly more sensitive treatment of other recent minipark reclamations, like the vest-pocket parks on Sixth Avenue in the Village.</p>
        <p>ANDREW ALPERN  Manhattan</p>
        <p>The writer, an architect and architectural historian, is the author of ''Luxury Apartment Houses of Manhattan'' (Dover, 1992).</p>
      </block>
